1
00:00:33,666 --> 00:00:35,166
[SHIRAISHI]
A sunfish?

2
00:00:36,458 --> 00:00:38,208
[SUGIMOTO] During the summer,
sunfish float up

3
00:00:38,291 --> 00:00:40,666
to the surface to take a nap.

4
00:00:40,750 --> 00:00:43,291
So it's easy to climb on top
of 'em and harvest the meat.

5
00:00:45,208 --> 00:00:48,791
Jeez. You'll really do anything
to eat in-season fish.

6
00:00:54,083 --> 00:00:56,000
[INKARMAT] Here. I sewed it
back up for you.

7
00:00:57,958 --> 00:00:59,750
Thank you.

8
00:00:59,833 --> 00:01:01,291
You've done so much for me.

9
00:01:01,375 --> 00:01:03,458
Not to mention, Cikapasi.

10
00:01:04,500 --> 00:01:06,125
[INKARMAT]
Not at all.

11
00:01:06,208 --> 00:01:10,208
I feel a lot safer on the road
having a man along.

12
00:01:10,291 --> 00:01:13,416
It's not that I haven't noticed
you're usually cold to me,

13
00:01:13,500 --> 00:01:15,250
but you're always kind
when it counts.

14
00:01:17,291 --> 00:01:18,333
Hmm.

15
00:01:19,416 --> 00:01:21,125
[FISHERMAN speaking
in Satsuma dialect]

16
00:01:24,875 --> 00:01:25,958
Huh?

17
00:01:26,041 --> 00:01:28,083
He's offering us
that sea otter meat.

18
00:01:28,166 --> 00:01:29,583
Sea otter?

19
00:01:29,666 --> 00:01:31,875
I've never tried it.

20
00:01:31,958 --> 00:01:33,083
Thank you.

21
00:01:33,166 --> 00:01:36,333
[speaking in Satsuma dialect]

22
00:01:36,416 --> 00:01:37,958
[gasps]

23
00:01:38,041 --> 00:01:39,458
[TANIGAKI]
What'd he say?

24
00:01:39,541 --> 00:01:40,666
Hmm.

25
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:45,166
You know what we need?

26
00:01:45,250 --> 00:01:46,625
Beach rose fruit.

27
00:01:50,958 --> 00:01:52,166
-Oh...
-Huh?

28
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:56,541
What is that?

29
00:01:56,625 --> 00:01:58,333
Looks like a big, black cloud.

30
00:01:58,416 --> 00:02:00,041
[growling]

31
00:02:03,625 --> 00:02:05,791
[grunts]

32
00:02:05,875 --> 00:02:08,500
Grasshopper.
I hate these things.

33
00:02:08,583 --> 00:02:09,916
[grunts]

34
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,083
And you call yourself
"immortal."

35
00:02:12,166 --> 00:02:14,333
Hey, guys, we got a problem.

36
00:02:14,416 --> 00:02:15,458
-Huh?
-Hmm?

37
00:02:17,583 --> 00:02:20,041
[ALL screaming]

38
00:03:53,125 --> 00:03:54,583
[screaming]

39
00:03:54,666 --> 00:03:56,041
[SUGIMOTO] They're trying
to bite through our clothes!

40
00:03:56,125 --> 00:03:57,958
-[screaming]
-[TANIGAKI] That police lodge.

41
00:03:58,041 --> 00:03:59,125
Let's take cover there!

42
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:00,541
Come on!

43
00:04:01,791 --> 00:04:03,541
Inkarmat is still
out here somewhere!

44
00:04:03,625 --> 00:04:06,000
[SUGIMOTO]
She'll be fine! Just get inside!

45
00:04:07,708 --> 00:04:10,041
-[TANIGAKI grunts]
-[SUGIMOTO] Ow! Ow! Ow! Go!

46
00:04:10,125 --> 00:04:11,666
[SHIRAISHI]
What the hell are those things?!

47
00:04:13,166 --> 00:04:14,916
♪

48
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:16,375
[OGATA]
A locust swarm.

49
00:04:17,833 --> 00:04:20,375
When the conditions are right,
like after a flood or something,

50
00:04:20,458 --> 00:04:23,291
you get a ton
of these nasty things.

51
00:04:23,375 --> 00:04:27,041
They move in huge swarms
and cover dozens of kilometers.

52
00:04:27,125 --> 00:04:28,625
They can even cross the sea.

53
00:04:29,791 --> 00:04:31,791
It's not just the crops
they eat.

54
00:04:31,875 --> 00:04:34,500
They'll eat through paper walls
and even kimonos.

55
00:04:35,625 --> 00:04:39,041
How long do you think it might
take for them to pass by?

56
00:04:39,125 --> 00:04:41,041
I'm really hungry.

57
00:04:41,125 --> 00:04:42,708
Where is Asirpa?

58
00:04:42,791 --> 00:04:43,958
I hope she's okay.

59
00:04:44,041 --> 00:04:45,291
[INKARMAT panting]

60
00:04:45,375 --> 00:04:47,041
♪

61
00:04:49,166 --> 00:04:50,291
[ASIRPA]
Inkarmat!

62
00:04:52,500 --> 00:04:53,541
Here.

63
00:04:57,541 --> 00:04:59,125
You really saved me.

64
00:04:59,208 --> 00:05:01,416
We should be safe out
on the water.

65
00:05:01,500 --> 00:05:03,916
I wanted to speak
with you alone, anyway.

66
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,083
Here's my chance.

67
00:05:06,166 --> 00:05:09,041
I want you to tell me everything
you know about my father.

68
00:05:16,125 --> 00:05:18,666
So sea otter meat
has kind of a unique smell,

69
00:05:18,750 --> 00:05:19,708
wouldn't you say?

70
00:05:19,791 --> 00:05:22,958
Are you sure it's even edible?

71
00:05:23,041 --> 00:05:24,250
[sighs]

72
00:05:24,333 --> 00:05:25,500
[SUGIMOTO]
What's going on?

73
00:05:26,500 --> 00:05:27,875
Something's weird.

74
00:05:27,958 --> 00:05:31,791
Why does Shiraishi look... sexy?

75
00:05:32,833 --> 00:05:36,125
[TANIGAKI]
Sugimoto, you okay?

76
00:05:36,208 --> 00:05:37,333
[gasps]

77
00:05:39,083 --> 00:05:40,083
Oh, my.

78
00:05:41,083 --> 00:05:42,375
I lost another button.

79
00:05:42,458 --> 00:05:43,958
[SHIRAISHI]
That Matagi.

80
00:05:44,041 --> 00:05:46,875
He's so dreamy.

81
00:05:46,958 --> 00:05:48,541
Oh!

82
00:05:48,625 --> 00:05:51,750
Ah, I feel dizzy. Weird.

83
00:05:51,833 --> 00:05:53,125
Ogata, you okay?

84
00:05:53,208 --> 00:05:55,708
[SUGIMOTO]
Lie down, immediately!

85
00:05:55,791 --> 00:05:57,208
[groans]

86
00:05:57,291 --> 00:05:59,375
Let's unbutton your shirt
so you can breathe better.

87
00:05:59,458 --> 00:06:00,750
Pants, too!

88
00:06:00,833 --> 00:06:02,750
I think it's important
he takes off everything!

89
00:06:02,833 --> 00:06:03,833
[gasps]

90
00:06:03,916 --> 00:06:05,291
[door opens, closes]

91
00:06:05,375 --> 00:06:07,000
[KIRORANKE]
Ow, that hurt.

92
00:06:07,083 --> 00:06:08,333
They nipped at my ears.

93
00:06:10,958 --> 00:06:13,541
Hey, there, what you guys up to?

94
00:06:13,625 --> 00:06:15,583
Kiroranke.

95
00:06:15,666 --> 00:06:16,958
[ALL gasp]

96
00:06:18,166 --> 00:06:21,625
The truth is, I knew
your father very well, Asirpa.

97
00:06:21,708 --> 00:06:25,791
In fact, I was close to your age
now the first time I met him.

98
00:06:25,875 --> 00:06:27,750
What about now, do you hate him?

99
00:06:27,833 --> 00:06:29,541
Of course not.

100
00:06:29,625 --> 00:06:33,250
I've always been on his side
and yours, don't you see?

101
00:06:33,333 --> 00:06:35,375
You think I'm that stupid?

102
00:06:35,458 --> 00:06:37,583
You used lies to scare Huci,

103
00:06:37,666 --> 00:06:40,041
and then you used
Tanigaki to follow me.

104
00:06:41,166 --> 00:06:43,166
[INKARMAT]
I never lied to Huci.

105
00:06:43,250 --> 00:06:45,666
You should return to Otaru.

106
00:06:45,750 --> 00:06:47,750
I don't believe
in fortune-telling.

107
00:06:47,833 --> 00:06:49,333
I need to know the truth,

108
00:06:49,416 --> 00:06:52,333
and I'm planning to find
it out for myself.

109
00:06:52,416 --> 00:06:55,708
[INKARMAT] Nopperabo,
the man in Abashiri Prison,

110
00:06:55,791 --> 00:06:57,458
he isn't your father, Asirpa.

111
00:06:57,541 --> 00:06:58,541
[gasps]

112
00:06:59,666 --> 00:07:01,791
[INKARMAT]
Your father's name was Wilk.

113
00:07:01,875 --> 00:07:04,625
He was never a man who'd be
morally capable of killing Ainu

114
00:07:04,708 --> 00:07:06,541
and stealing their gold.

115
00:07:06,625 --> 00:07:09,250
I remember the day
I first met him.

116
00:07:09,333 --> 00:07:11,750
Wilk had only
just arrived in Hokkaido,

117
00:07:11,833 --> 00:07:15,000
and he spoke Ainu
with a Sakhalin accent.

118
00:07:15,083 --> 00:07:17,500
He had deep, blue eyes,
just like yours.

119
00:07:17,583 --> 00:07:19,333
[gasps]

120
00:07:19,416 --> 00:07:21,875
He told me that he'd been born
to a Polish father

121
00:07:21,958 --> 00:07:23,791
and a Sakhalin Ainu mother.

122
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:27,916
He explained that many of
the people living on Sakhalin

123
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,000
were Poles who had been
oppressed by the czar

124
00:07:30,083 --> 00:07:32,208
and exiled to the Far East.

125
00:07:32,291 --> 00:07:34,875
Wilk had worked with other
ethnic minorities

126
00:07:34,958 --> 00:07:36,583
since he was young,

127
00:07:36,666 --> 00:07:39,375
fighting alongside them for
their liberation from the czar.

128
00:07:39,458 --> 00:07:41,833
He was wounded in that fight

129
00:07:41,916 --> 00:07:44,166
and fled to Otaru in Hokkaido.

130
00:07:46,791 --> 00:07:50,791
At the time, I'd already begun
traveling as a fortune-teller,

131
00:07:50,875 --> 00:07:52,916
and we spent every day together.

132
00:07:53,916 --> 00:07:55,875
Wilk listened to everything
I told him

133
00:07:55,958 --> 00:07:57,791
about the Ainu and our ways.

134
00:07:57,875 --> 00:08:02,458
Our beliefs, customs,
language, food, everything.

135
00:08:04,208 --> 00:08:06,166
He recovered
from his wounds here.

136
00:08:06,250 --> 00:08:09,375
And the more he learned
of the Hokkaido Ainu,

137
00:08:09,458 --> 00:08:11,125
the more he came to love them.

138
00:08:11,208 --> 00:08:13,041
♪

139
00:08:15,208 --> 00:08:17,250
[ASIRPA] I don't believe
that my father is Nopperabo

140
00:08:17,333 --> 00:08:19,041
any more than you do.

141
00:08:19,125 --> 00:08:23,416
But still, my father never
once told me anything about you.

142
00:08:23,500 --> 00:08:25,541
He always claimed
that he learned everything

143
00:08:25,625 --> 00:08:27,708
about the Ainu
from my mother.

144
00:08:27,791 --> 00:08:30,250
I don't think I can believe
anything you say.

145
00:08:31,375 --> 00:08:32,291
[gasps]

146
00:08:34,916 --> 00:08:38,416
I guess to Wilk I was still
just a child and not important.

147
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,208
Maybe he really forgot about me.

148
00:08:44,500 --> 00:08:47,166
If you agree Nopperabo
is a different person,

149
00:08:47,250 --> 00:08:49,000
then where is
my father right now?

150
00:08:51,791 --> 00:08:53,083
He's gone.

151
00:08:54,250 --> 00:08:55,666
My poor Wilk.

152
00:08:55,750 --> 00:08:56,916
He was murdered.

153
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,041
[gasps]

154
00:08:59,416 --> 00:09:01,708
By Kiroranke, a former friend.

155
00:09:01,791 --> 00:09:03,500
♪

156
00:09:08,416 --> 00:09:11,416
[KIRORANKE] I got separated from
Hijikata's group at Asahikawa,

157
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:13,583
and I haven't seen
any of them since.

158
00:09:13,666 --> 00:09:15,000
I guessed that you'd most likely

159
00:09:15,083 --> 00:09:16,500
head down
the mountains to Tokachi

160
00:09:16,583 --> 00:09:18,875
in order to avoid
running into the Seventh.

161
00:09:18,958 --> 00:09:21,208
Then, I heard a rumor
at a local kotan

162
00:09:21,291 --> 00:09:23,291
that someone
had actually seen you.

163
00:09:23,375 --> 00:09:26,458
Anyway, let's get back
to the present.

164
00:09:26,541 --> 00:09:30,958
Sugimoto, is it just me,
or have you grown sexier

165
00:09:31,041 --> 00:09:32,750
since the last time we met?

166
00:09:33,833 --> 00:09:35,041
Come on, stop.

167
00:09:35,125 --> 00:09:36,583
[SHIRAISHI]
So cute!

168
00:09:36,666 --> 00:09:38,333
-[KIRORANKE] So cute.
-[TANIGAKI] So cute.

169
00:09:38,416 --> 00:09:39,791
And you, Kiro,

170
00:09:39,875 --> 00:09:41,833
you kinda look like you've been
working out, too,

171
00:09:41,916 --> 00:09:43,125
am I right, huh?

172
00:09:43,208 --> 00:09:45,125
Oh, do you really think so?

173
00:09:45,208 --> 00:09:46,750
You agree, Tanigaki?

174
00:09:46,833 --> 00:09:48,125
[groaning]

175
00:09:48,208 --> 00:09:49,375
[TANIGAKI]
What's happening?

176
00:09:49,458 --> 00:09:52,625
This feeling,
I can't control it.

177
00:09:52,708 --> 00:09:54,791
[SHIRAISHI]
I've never felt this before.

178
00:09:54,875 --> 00:09:56,375
What do I do?

179
00:09:56,458 --> 00:09:58,958
Things are about to get weird
if it doesn't go away.

180
00:09:59,041 --> 00:10:00,541
[exhales sharply]

181
00:10:00,625 --> 00:10:03,083
♪

182
00:10:04,500 --> 00:10:06,250
Yeah, that's it.

183
00:10:06,333 --> 00:10:08,416
I can't control it anymore.

184
00:10:08,500 --> 00:10:10,250
I have to be free!

185
00:10:12,333 --> 00:10:14,583
-Let's play sumo!
-[ALL] Yes.

186
00:10:14,666 --> 00:10:16,291
[ALL]
Great idea!

187
00:10:17,875 --> 00:10:20,250
[grunting]

188
00:10:20,333 --> 00:10:22,208
[groaning]

189
00:10:22,291 --> 00:10:25,500
[grunting]

190
00:10:25,583 --> 00:10:26,625
[laughing]

191
00:10:26,708 --> 00:10:28,666
[groaning]

192
00:10:32,916 --> 00:10:34,375
[ALL sighing]

193
00:10:37,166 --> 00:10:39,666
♪

194
00:10:39,750 --> 00:10:41,708
[ALL]
That was so hot.

195
00:10:45,541 --> 00:10:49,875
[SHIRAISHI] Hey. Looks like
the grasshoppers are gone.

196
00:10:49,958 --> 00:10:52,625
Yeah. Seems that way.

197
00:10:52,708 --> 00:10:55,833
We got a little
outta control in there.

198
00:10:55,916 --> 00:10:57,875
[ALL]
Yeah...

199
00:10:58,875 --> 00:11:00,458
Tell no one of this.

200
00:11:00,541 --> 00:11:01,833
-[chuckles]
-Hmm.

201
00:11:15,416 --> 00:11:17,500
Inkarmat?

202
00:11:17,583 --> 00:11:19,875
[INKARMAT] It's believed
that the meat of sea otters

203
00:11:19,958 --> 00:11:22,583
acts as a powerful aphrodisiac.

204
00:11:22,666 --> 00:11:25,250
Did you know,
when one loses a partner,

205
00:11:25,333 --> 00:11:28,416
they have no outlet for
their lust, and so, they die.

206
00:11:31,125 --> 00:11:33,166
Whoa, hey. Hold on.

207
00:11:33,250 --> 00:11:34,291
What are you doing?

208
00:11:34,375 --> 00:11:36,833
If it makes you feel better,

209
00:11:36,916 --> 00:11:39,791
you can always just blame it
on the sea otter meat.

210
00:11:41,041 --> 00:11:41,958
[moaning softly]

211
00:11:43,333 --> 00:11:44,458
[gasps]

212
00:11:50,875 --> 00:11:52,750
[BOTH moaning]

213
00:11:57,500 --> 00:11:59,833
♪

214
00:12:02,291 --> 00:12:04,000
[INKARMAT]
If you go to Abashiri,

215
00:12:04,083 --> 00:12:06,541
you'll run into Kiroranke again.

216
00:12:06,625 --> 00:12:08,250
He's a dangerous man.

217
00:12:09,458 --> 00:12:13,500
In the end, you'll lose
both the gold and the tattoos.

218
00:12:14,833 --> 00:12:17,791
I can't imagine Kiroranke Nispa
killing my father.

219
00:12:19,166 --> 00:12:20,500
[INKARMAT]
I have proof.

220
00:12:22,625 --> 00:12:24,208
-[INKARMAT] Asirpa.
-Huh?

221
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:27,500
Have you been here all night?

222
00:12:27,583 --> 00:12:29,416
Hey. Look at that, guys.

223
00:12:29,500 --> 00:12:31,000
Asirpa's doing just fine.

224
00:12:31,083 --> 00:12:32,833
Thank goodness for that.

225
00:12:32,916 --> 00:12:34,333
-Glad you're safe.
-[gasps]

226
00:12:36,583 --> 00:12:37,625
[INKARMAT]
Kiroranke.

227
00:12:37,708 --> 00:12:39,416
What is he doing here?

228
00:12:40,666 --> 00:12:42,958
Hey, there. How have you been?

229
00:12:44,166 --> 00:12:45,166
Huh?

230
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:49,125
Kiroranke Nispa.

231
00:12:49,208 --> 00:12:51,416
Are you the one
who killed my father?

232
00:12:51,500 --> 00:12:52,958
[gasps]

233
00:12:53,041 --> 00:12:54,583
You're serious?

234
00:12:54,666 --> 00:12:56,750
Come on, now, where is
this coming from?

235
00:12:56,833 --> 00:13:00,166
[INKARMAT] She confronts him
directly right after I tell her?

236
00:13:00,250 --> 00:13:02,250
That foolish girl.

237
00:13:02,333 --> 00:13:04,833
-Here's the proof.
-[gasps]

238
00:13:04,916 --> 00:13:06,916
The fingerprints
left on this betting ticket.

239
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:08,166
What?

240
00:13:08,250 --> 00:13:09,583
Fingerprints?

241
00:13:09,666 --> 00:13:11,541
Inkarmat.

242
00:13:11,625 --> 00:13:15,083
Every set of fingerprints
is entirely unique unto itself.

243
00:13:15,166 --> 00:13:17,583
They've been used for years
outside of Japan.

244
00:13:17,666 --> 00:13:20,375
It's very helpful
in criminal investigations.

245
00:13:21,458 --> 00:13:23,833
At the horse racing track
in Naganuma,

246
00:13:23,916 --> 00:13:26,083
I took fingerprints
from all of the men,

247
00:13:26,166 --> 00:13:28,083
and I had them matched.

248
00:13:28,166 --> 00:13:31,125
To my surprise, Kiroranke's
ended up matching some

249
00:13:31,208 --> 00:13:32,416
which were found
several years ago

250
00:13:32,500 --> 00:13:34,500
in a rather shocking place.

251
00:13:35,500 --> 00:13:38,875
The place where Asirpa's father
had been murdered.

252
00:13:38,958 --> 00:13:41,166
-[gasps]
-What are you suggesting?

253
00:13:42,458 --> 00:13:45,541
She said your prints were found
on his makiri blade.

254
00:13:45,625 --> 00:13:48,916
You claimed you hadn't seen
my father for years, right?

255
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:50,541
This is nuts.

256
00:13:50,625 --> 00:13:52,875
I mean, if I'm the killer,
then who's Nopperabo?

257
00:13:52,958 --> 00:13:54,291
The guy that's in prison?

258
00:13:54,375 --> 00:13:55,750
[OGATA]
Everyone, hold it.

259
00:13:55,833 --> 00:13:57,625
-[rifle cocks]
-This is about her.

260
00:13:57,708 --> 00:13:59,875
She's been working
with Lieutenant Tsurumi.

261
00:13:59,958 --> 00:14:02,333
Stop this.
What proof do you have?

262
00:14:02,416 --> 00:14:05,166
Oh, poor Genjirou Tanigaki.

263
00:14:05,250 --> 00:14:07,625
She's got you wrapped around
her little finger, huh?

264
00:14:07,708 --> 00:14:09,333
It was Lieutenant Tsurumi

265
00:14:09,416 --> 00:14:12,375
who recovered the items
left at the murder scene.

266
00:14:12,458 --> 00:14:14,875
In other words,
he's the only one

267
00:14:14,958 --> 00:14:16,875
with the recorded fingerprints.

268
00:14:16,958 --> 00:14:18,291
[gasps]

269
00:14:20,583 --> 00:14:22,666
I was just using
Lieutenant Tsurumi.

270
00:14:22,750 --> 00:14:24,250
[TANIGAKI gasps]

271
00:14:24,333 --> 00:14:27,500
Gotta admit, she's a hell
of a woman, ain't she, Tanigaki?

272
00:14:28,666 --> 00:14:31,666
How can you trust
any information from that man?

273
00:14:31,750 --> 00:14:35,375
If we start killing each other,
we're giving him what he wants.

274
00:14:35,458 --> 00:14:37,000
Hear me out.

275
00:14:37,083 --> 00:14:39,625
Asirpa, I don't blame you

276
00:14:39,708 --> 00:14:42,916
for not wanting to believe
your father is Nopperabo.

277
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:46,125
But there can't be
that many people in the world

278
00:14:46,208 --> 00:14:47,833
capable of coming up
with the idea

279
00:14:47,916 --> 00:14:50,083
of tattooing a code
on human skin.

280
00:14:50,166 --> 00:14:51,625
Do you hear me?

281
00:14:51,708 --> 00:14:53,583
I think you know that, right?

282
00:14:55,791 --> 00:14:58,000
This is tense.
What do you think?

283
00:14:58,083 --> 00:14:59,625
I mean, which one
is telling the truth?

284
00:14:59,708 --> 00:15:01,375
♪

285
00:15:02,916 --> 00:15:05,000
Shiraishi.

286
00:15:05,083 --> 00:15:08,000
You're the only one who actually
met Nopperabo in jail.

287
00:15:08,083 --> 00:15:09,333
Maybe you could help here.

288
00:15:09,416 --> 00:15:11,208
[SUGIMOTO]
That's true.

289
00:15:11,291 --> 00:15:13,458
Did he really have
blue eyes like Asirpa?

290
00:15:13,541 --> 00:15:15,458
Uh... I don't know.

291
00:15:15,541 --> 00:15:18,375
I never said anything about him
having blue eyes.

292
00:15:18,458 --> 00:15:20,541
To be honest,
he isn't exactly the kinda guy

293
00:15:20,625 --> 00:15:23,083
you wanna spend
a lot of time staring at.

294
00:15:23,166 --> 00:15:26,166
[SUGIMOTO]
Nopperabo. The man with no face.

295
00:15:26,250 --> 00:15:28,125
[SHIRAISHI] From what I know,
all he actually did

296
00:15:28,208 --> 00:15:30,041
was make the tattoos.

297
00:15:30,125 --> 00:15:31,875
As far as the escape plan goes,

298
00:15:31,958 --> 00:15:34,125
old No Face wasn't
the one behind it.

299
00:15:34,208 --> 00:15:36,458
The mastermind for that
was Hijikata.

300
00:15:39,625 --> 00:15:41,541
[SUGIMOTO]
Makes you wonder.

301
00:15:41,625 --> 00:15:44,875
Maybe Toshizou Hijikata
set the whole thing up.

302
00:15:49,291 --> 00:15:51,791
[TANIGAKI] I don't know
what you want, Inkarmat.

303
00:15:51,875 --> 00:15:54,333
I just want to protect the gold.

304
00:15:54,416 --> 00:15:57,083
I'm an Ainu woman, after all.

305
00:15:57,166 --> 00:15:59,541
What about
Asirpa's father, Wilk?

306
00:15:59,625 --> 00:16:02,041
Did he feel the same way as you?

307
00:16:02,125 --> 00:16:03,250
Yes.

308
00:16:03,333 --> 00:16:05,375
That's why he was killed
by Kiroranke,

309
00:16:05,458 --> 00:16:08,291
a fellow member
of his guerrilla organization.

310
00:16:08,375 --> 00:16:10,000
That's what I think, anyway.

311
00:16:10,083 --> 00:16:12,083
You know what I think?

312
00:16:12,166 --> 00:16:14,333
Tsurumi might've falsified
those fingerprints.

313
00:16:14,416 --> 00:16:16,833
Sure, it's possible.

314
00:16:16,916 --> 00:16:21,666
But if I end up dead
sometime in the near future,

315
00:16:21,750 --> 00:16:24,500
know it'll be Kiroranke
who kills me.

316
00:16:25,625 --> 00:16:28,458
[TANIGAKI] Did you sleep with me
to protect yourself from him?

317
00:16:28,541 --> 00:16:29,958
Tell me the truth.

318
00:16:31,458 --> 00:16:32,916
'Course not.

319
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:36,291
What happened last night
was due to the sea otter.

320
00:16:36,375 --> 00:16:37,541
[TANIGAKI]
Sea otter!

321
00:16:40,083 --> 00:16:41,583
[HAJIME]
Another telegram arrived

322
00:16:41,666 --> 00:16:45,083
for the old Ainu lady in Otaru
from Tanigaki in Kushiro.

323
00:16:45,166 --> 00:16:47,583
It would appear that he's met up
with them, now.

324
00:16:47,666 --> 00:16:48,750
[TSURUMI]
Good.

325
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:51,500
Then, I think
it's just about time

326
00:16:51,583 --> 00:16:53,708
we head to Abashiri, too.

327
00:16:54,916 --> 00:16:58,000
[KIRORANKE]
My sons are all Hokkaido Ainu.

328
00:16:58,083 --> 00:17:02,250
So I believe the gold belongs
to the Ainu of this land.

329
00:17:02,333 --> 00:17:05,416
My goal is exactly
the same as yours.

330
00:17:05,500 --> 00:17:08,000
Okay, so what do we do now?

331
00:17:08,083 --> 00:17:10,375
With everyone being suspicious
of each other.

332
00:17:10,458 --> 00:17:11,875
That's a good point.

333
00:17:11,958 --> 00:17:13,833
I'd really prefer not to get
murdered in my sleep.

334
00:17:13,916 --> 00:17:15,583
♪

335
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:22,708
I say we keep moving.

336
00:17:22,791 --> 00:17:26,083
Once we meet Nopperabo,
it'll all be clear.

337
00:17:26,166 --> 00:17:28,416
Asirpa will know the truth.

338
00:17:28,500 --> 00:17:30,500
Our goal hasn't changed at all.

339
00:17:30,583 --> 00:17:33,166
We're going to Abashiri.

340
00:17:33,250 --> 00:17:34,500
So, let's do it.

341
00:17:34,583 --> 00:17:36,875
Inkarmat and Kiroranke?

342
00:17:36,958 --> 00:17:38,208
A little warning.

343
00:17:38,291 --> 00:17:40,875
If either of you end up dead
on this journey,

344
00:17:40,958 --> 00:17:42,291
I promise you,

345
00:17:42,375 --> 00:17:44,916
I have no problem
killing whoever's left.

346
00:17:46,125 --> 00:17:47,125
I'm just kidding.

347
00:17:47,208 --> 00:17:50,583
[laughing]

348
00:17:50,666 --> 00:17:52,958
♪

349
00:17:55,333 --> 00:17:57,416
[footsteps]

350
00:18:01,666 --> 00:18:02,916
Huh?

351
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:04,500
-[KADOKURA] New kid!
-[gasps]

352
00:18:06,250 --> 00:18:08,833
Are you still curious
about that guy?

353
00:18:08,916 --> 00:18:10,208
Yeah, I guess so.

354
00:18:10,291 --> 00:18:12,541
Don't see many people
with faces like that.

355
00:18:12,625 --> 00:18:14,708
Makes me wanna
get a better look.

356
00:18:14,791 --> 00:18:16,541
[sighs]
Kid.

357
00:18:16,625 --> 00:18:19,500
Take it from me,
I've been here for a while.

358
00:18:19,583 --> 00:18:23,041
The first thing you need to
learn about this place is...

359
00:18:23,125 --> 00:18:25,583
stay the hell away
from Nopperabo.

360
00:18:28,541 --> 00:18:31,333
♪

361
00:18:43,500 --> 00:18:45,458
[whistling]

362
00:18:49,791 --> 00:18:51,458
They move him around.

363
00:18:51,541 --> 00:18:54,791
Every single day, they transfer
him to a different cell.

364
00:18:54,875 --> 00:18:57,041
If we can detect
any kind of pattern

365
00:18:57,125 --> 00:18:58,666
to the way
they're moving him,

366
00:18:58,750 --> 00:19:01,166
we may be able to predict
where he'll be in a few days.

367
00:19:03,708 --> 00:19:05,041
[sighs]

368
00:19:08,500 --> 00:19:11,666
[KID]
Hmm? So this is a pig farm, huh?

369
00:19:11,750 --> 00:19:14,125
There are a bunch of crates
piled in back there.

370
00:19:14,208 --> 00:19:16,458
I need you to go
pile them outside.

371
00:19:16,541 --> 00:19:18,125
Sure, no problem.

372
00:19:21,125 --> 00:19:22,666
-New kid.
-[gasps]

373
00:19:22,750 --> 00:19:25,083
Leave your katana here with me.

374
00:19:25,166 --> 00:19:26,416
If you happen to trip over it,

375
00:19:26,500 --> 00:19:28,416
you'll only end up
covered in pig shit.

376
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:29,583
Oh, thanks.

377
00:19:29,666 --> 00:19:30,958
[pig grunts]

378
00:19:33,041 --> 00:19:35,291
[KID] Hey, where are
those crates, again?

379
00:19:35,375 --> 00:19:37,041
Chief Kadokura?

380
00:19:38,416 --> 00:19:40,958
[INUDOU] So that new kid
is working with the Seventh?

381
00:19:41,041 --> 00:19:43,250
Well, that's
very interesting, indeed.

382
00:19:43,333 --> 00:19:45,500
I want you to take care of him.

383
00:19:45,583 --> 00:19:47,708
Security Chief Kadokura.

384
00:19:47,791 --> 00:19:50,166
You're saying you want me
to do it myself?

385
00:19:50,250 --> 00:19:52,791
No, you can use the prisoners.

386
00:19:52,875 --> 00:19:56,250
You've got a jail full of people
who are good at murder.

387
00:19:56,333 --> 00:19:59,708
This is my prison
and I run it my way.

388
00:19:59,791 --> 00:20:01,916
Anybody who tries
to mess with me,

389
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:04,458
will be reduced
to a pile of pig food.

390
00:20:06,125 --> 00:20:08,541
[KADOKURA] Sorry, new kid,
but I don't have a choice.

391
00:20:10,041 --> 00:20:11,208
Hmm.

392
00:20:12,500 --> 00:20:13,500
[gasps]

393
00:20:13,583 --> 00:20:15,166
[grunting]

394
00:20:15,250 --> 00:20:16,625
[KID]
Um...

395
00:20:16,708 --> 00:20:18,333
Chief Kadokura?

396
00:20:18,416 --> 00:20:20,333
♪

397
00:20:20,416 --> 00:20:21,625
[heavy breathing]

398
00:20:21,708 --> 00:20:24,208
Uh, need some help here!

399
00:20:24,291 --> 00:20:25,791
Chief Kadokura?!

400
00:20:25,875 --> 00:20:27,416
It's gone.

401
00:20:27,500 --> 00:20:28,416
My katana.

402
00:20:28,500 --> 00:20:29,333
[gasps]

403
00:20:29,416 --> 00:20:31,416
[grunting]

404
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:34,458
♪

405
00:20:40,208 --> 00:20:41,500
[gasps]

406
00:20:46,708 --> 00:20:48,666
Oh, Chief Kadokura?

407
00:20:48,750 --> 00:20:50,166
[KADOKURA]
You've gotta be kidding me.

408
00:20:50,250 --> 00:20:53,625
This kid is unbelievably strong.

409
00:20:53,708 --> 00:20:56,416
Forget this, I don't pick fights
I can't win.

410
00:20:57,916 --> 00:20:59,708
[KADOKURA]
Well, it's done.

411
00:20:59,791 --> 00:21:02,916
I fed him to the pigs,
as you instructed.

412
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:04,875
He fought harder
than I expected,

413
00:21:04,958 --> 00:21:08,416
and he was badly wounded,
so were both prisoners.

414
00:21:08,500 --> 00:21:12,000
In fact, in the end, I just had
to finish off all three.

415
00:21:12,083 --> 00:21:13,625
I reported the new kid
as missing

416
00:21:13,708 --> 00:21:16,375
and the other two
as having died after a brawl.

417
00:21:16,458 --> 00:21:18,125
Seems believable.

418
00:21:18,208 --> 00:21:19,916
When'd you get here?

419
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:21,291
Seven years ago?

420
00:21:21,375 --> 00:21:22,708
Does that sound about right?

421
00:21:22,791 --> 00:21:24,375
Yes, sir.

422
00:21:24,458 --> 00:21:27,458
I always thought of you
as a wimpy tanuki of a man,

423
00:21:27,541 --> 00:21:29,750
with limp, flaccid balls.

424
00:21:29,833 --> 00:21:32,333
I assumed if I looked up
"useless" in the dictionary,

425
00:21:32,416 --> 00:21:34,416
I'd see your face.

426
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:35,958
However, today it appears

427
00:21:36,041 --> 00:21:38,500
I'm going to have to
adjust my opinion of you.

428
00:21:38,583 --> 00:21:40,041
Just a little bit.

429
00:21:41,125 --> 00:21:43,250
Thank you very much, sir.

430
00:21:43,333 --> 00:21:45,166
I will never forget this.

431
00:21:46,416 --> 00:21:48,041
Well, this is sad.

432
00:21:48,125 --> 00:21:51,291
I had a lot more research
to do here.

433
00:21:51,375 --> 00:21:53,833
I woefully underestimated
Chief Kadokura.

434
00:21:55,250 --> 00:21:57,541
Lieutenant Tsurumi
is going to scold me!

435
00:23:36,416 --> 00:23:39,041
-[ticking]
-Huh?

436
00:23:39,125 --> 00:23:40,375
What is that noise?

437
00:23:41,750 --> 00:23:43,416
-[neighing]
-[groans]

438
00:23:43,500 --> 00:23:46,083
Oh! Damn it,
I can't see a thing!

439
00:23:46,166 --> 00:23:47,083
Where are they?

440
00:23:47,166 --> 00:23:49,833
[ticking continues]

441
00:23:49,916 --> 00:23:52,083
[MAN]
Leave the horses and the money.

442
00:23:52,166 --> 00:23:54,583
[screaming]

443
00:23:54,666 --> 00:23:56,166
[grunts]

444
00:23:59,583 --> 00:24:01,916
♪

445
00:24:06,708 --> 00:24:10,125
[NARRATOR] Next time,
"The Sound of an Ambush."

